        <h2 class="font-display font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-gray-800 mb-6">
          The Science of Cold Recovery for Women
        </h2>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          When you immerse yourself in cold water after physical activity, several powerful physiological processes are triggered that specifically benefit recovery and stress management. Understanding these mechanisms helps you optimize your cold therapy practice for maximum benefit.
        </p>
        
        <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-xl text-gray-800 mb-4">Inflammation Reduction</h3>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Cold exposure causes vasoconstriction, which reduces blood flow to inflamed tissues and limits the inflammatory response. This is particularly beneficial for women, who may experience more pronounced inflammatory responses due to hormonal fluctuations throughout their cycle.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-xl text-gray-800 mb-4">Enhanced Circulation</h3>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          The alternating vasoconstriction and vasodilation that occurs with cold exposure acts like a vascular pump, improving circulation and nutrient delivery to recovering tissues. This enhanced blood flow accelerates the removal of metabolic waste products that contribute to muscle soreness.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-blue-50 p-6 rounded-lg mb-6">
          <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-xl text-blue-800 mb-3">Key Recovery Mechanisms:</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-700">
            <li>• Reduced muscle damage markers (creatine kinase, LDH)</li>
            <li>• Decreased inflammatory cytokines</li>
            <li>• Enhanced lymphatic drainage</li>
            <li>• Improved pain tolerance through endorphin release</li>
            <li>• Faster restoration of muscle function</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: Stress Relief Benefits -->
